      "titleArabic": "الْجُمْلَة الْفِعْلِيَّة",
      "content": [
        "A verbal sentence (جملة فعلية) begins with a verb. The typical word order is: Verb + Subject (فاعل) + Object (مفعول به). This is the most common sentence structure in classical Arabic.",
        "When the verb comes first, it remains singular even if the subject is plural: ذَهَبَ الطُّلَّابُ (the students went) - not ذَهَبُوا الطُّلَّابُ."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Verbal sentences start with the verb: ذَهَبَ الطَّالِبُ",
        "Word order: Verb + Subject + Object",
        "The verb stays singular when preceding the subject",
        "The subject (فاعل) is in the nominative case (مرفوع)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "ذَهَبَ الطَّالِبُ", "english": "The student went" },
        { "arabic": "كَتَبَ الْمُدَرِّسُ الدَّرْسَ", "english": "The teacher wrote the lesson" },
        { "arabic": "قَرَأَتِ الْبِنْتُ الْكِتَابَ", "english": "The girl read the book" },
        { "arabic": "دَخَلَ الرِّجَالُ الْمَسْجِدَ", "english": "The men entered the mosque" }
      ]
    }
